## Summary: CDC Preliminary Estimated Flu Disease Burden 2025–2026 Season (November 21, 2025)

### Key Facts & Statistics

- **Data publication date:** November 21, 2025
- **Season start date for cumulative estimates:** October 1, 2025
- **Historical range of end-of-season flu-related hospitalizations (2010–2025):** 120,000–710,000
- The page provides **weekly, preliminary estimates** of cumulative flu illnesses, medical visits, hospitalizations, and deaths
- Estimates are expressed as **ranges** (lower to upper bound) rather than point values, due to ongoing flu circulation and data limitations early in the season

### Methodology
- CDC uses mathematical models based on **Flu Surv-NET** data, covering approximately **10% of the U.S. population**
- Crude hospitalization rates are adjusted for flu testing frequency and diagnostic test sensitivity, then scaled using ratios of hospitalizations to symptomatic illnesses
- Real-time testing practice data are **not available**; prior season data are used as proxies, which may introduce inaccuracy

### Key Limitations
- Cumulative hospitalization rates may be **underestimated** due to identification and reporting delays
- If current-season testing rates differ from past seasons, estimates may be inaccurate
- Preliminary estimates are **finalized** only when contemporary testing data become available and **may decrease** if testing has increased

### Notable Context for Forecasting
- The article does **not provide specific numerical estimates** for the 2025–26 season as of this publication date (suggesting data may be too limited early in the season to publish figures)
- The historical upper bound of end-of-season hospitalizations across all prior seasons (2010–2025) is **710,000**, which is **below the 850,000 threshold** in the resolution criteria

> **Disclaimer:** The article does not include the actual current-season hospitalization estimate range for 2025–26, only the methodology and historical context. The specific weekly figures may be displayed graphically on the CDC page but were not captured in the extracted text.
